## The Release That Quietly Raised the Bar

I've been running Playwright across three different projects for the past two years, and I've developed a habit of reading release notes with healthy skepticism. Most minor releases bring incremental improvements—a fixed selector edge case here, a slightly better error message there. Playwright 1.44 is different. A handful of the new capabilities address problems I've been working around for months, and at least one of them made me immediately open a PR to refactor existing test infrastructure.

That said, "new features" doesn't automatically mean "you should adopt all of them this week." Some additions in 1.44 solve real pain points you may already have; others are technically interesting but won't move the needle on your test suite's reliability or speed. I want to separate those two categories clearly rather than giving you a feature walkthrough that reads like a changelog summary.

Let's get into the specifics.

---

## aria Snapshots: The Accessibility-Aware Assertion You've Been Missing

The most immediately practical addition in Playwright 1.44 is `expect(locator).toMatchAriaSnapshot()`. If you've worked on teams that care about both functional testing and accessibility compliance, you'll recognize the gap this fills.

Previously, asserting on the semantic structure of a page required either pulling in a dedicated accessibility testing library like axe-core or writing brittle DOM-based assertions that checked ARIA attributes by brute force. Neither approach was elegant. The axe integration is powerful but heavyweight if your goal is structural snapshot testing rather than full WCAG auditing. The manual ARIA attribute checks are fragile and get stale fast.

`toMatchAriaSnapshot()` generates and compares a YAML representation of the accessibility tree. A basic usage looks like this:

```typescript
await expect(page.locator('nav')).toMatchAriaSnapshot(`
  - navigation:
    - link "Home"
    - link "Products"
    - link "Contact"
`);
```

What I find useful here isn't just the cleaner syntax—it's that you're asserting against the *semantic* structure rather than the visual or DOM structure. If a developer refactors a navigation component from `<ul>/<li>` to a different HTML structure but keeps the ARIA roles intact, your test still passes. If they accidentally strip the landmark roles in the refactor, your test catches it. That's the right behavior.

The snapshot update workflow also integrates cleanly with `--update-snapshots`, which means maintaining these doesn't become a chore. After a deliberate redesign, running `npx playwright test --update-snapshots` regenerates the baselines in one pass.

Where I'd be cautious: don't use this as a wholesale replacement for axe-core if you have real accessibility compliance requirements. The aria snapshot approach validates structure and presence, but it won't catch color contrast failures or missing alt text on dynamically loaded images. Use both tools for what they're each good at.

---

## Clock API Improvements: Testing Time Without Fighting It

Playwright's clock manipulation was already decent before 1.44, but the improvements to `page.clock` make a legitimate difference for anyone testing time-dependent UI behavior.

The key addition is granular control over time progression. You can now call `clock.runFor(milliseconds)` to advance time by a specific amount without triggering all pending timers indiscriminately, and `clock.fastForward()` has been made more predictable in how it handles nested timeouts. If you've ever written tests around session expiry banners, countdown timers, or delayed notification popups, you know how unpredictable the old approach could be.

A pattern I've already started using in our suite:

```typescript
test('shows session warning at 25 minutes of inactivity', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.clock.install({ time: new Date('2024-01-15T10:00:00') });
  await page.goto('/dashboard');

  await page.clock.fastForward('25:00');

  await expect(page.getByRole('alert', { name: /session expiring/i })).toBeVisible();
});
```

The improvement over Playwright 1.42's clock behavior is subtle but real: `fastForward` in previous versions could behave inconsistently when components used both `setTimeout` and `setInterval` together. The 1.44 fix brings it closer to how Sinon.js handles this, which most of us are more familiar with from unit testing contexts.

One thing worth noting: `page.clock.install()` needs to be called before navigation if you want to control the clock from page load. If you call it after `goto()`, some timers initialized during page load will have already fired. I've seen this catch teams out when they first adopt the clock API.

---

## `--only-failures` and Test Filtering Improvements in the CLI

This one is less glamorous but has meaningfully improved my daily workflow: Playwright 1.44 adds `--only-failures` as a CLI flag that re-runs only the tests that failed in the previous run.

This sounds like a small quality-of-life improvement, and it is. But in the context of a test suite with 800+ tests running across multiple browsers in GitHub Actions, the ability to iterate on failing tests without re-running everything is not trivial. Before this flag existed, the common workaround was either tagging failing tests with `@failing` and filtering by tag, or copy-pasting test names into `--grep` patterns—both of which require manual intervention that slows down the debug cycle.

With 1.44, the workflow is:

```bash
# First run—full suite
npx playwright test

# Iterate on failures only
npx playwright test --only-failures
```

Playwright stores the last run's results in a local cache, and `--only-failures` reads from that cache to determine which tests to re-execute. This works correctly in CI too, as long as the cache artifact is preserved between jobs—something you'll want to configure explicitly in your GitHub Actions or GitLab CI pipeline if you're using matrix builds across multiple workers.

Paired with `--repeat-each` for verifying flakiness on specific failures, this flag has become part of my standard debugging flow.

---

## WebSocket Route Interception: Finally, First-Class WebSocket Mocking

The feature I've waited longest for: `page.routeWebSocket()` gives you proper interception and mocking for WebSocket connections.

Before this, testing WebSocket-dependent UIs in Playwright was genuinely painful. The options were: run a real WebSocket server as a test fixture (slow, adds infrastructure complexity), use a library like `mock-socket` injected into the page context (works but requires modifying production code or adding test-only hooks), or avoid testing those flows altogether (the option too many teams quietly choose).

`routeWebSocket()` intercepts WebSocket connections at the browser level and lets you control what messages the client receives:

```typescript
await page.routeWebSocket('/ws/notifications', ws => {
  ws.onMessage(message => {
    // Echo back a mock response
    ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'ack', id: JSON.parse(message).id }));
  });

  // Simulate a server-initiated push after 2 seconds
  setTimeout(() => {
    ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'notification', text: 'Build completed' }));
  }, 2000);
});

await page.goto('/dashboard');
await expect(page.getByText('Build completed')).toBeVisible();
```

The API is clean and the interception happens at the network layer, not through JavaScript injection, which means it works regardless of how the application initializes its WebSocket connection. You can also close connections on demand to test reconnection logic, which covers a class of edge cases that were nearly impossible to test reliably before.

For teams building applications that use WebSockets for real-time features—live dashboards, collaborative editing, chat—this is the feature in 1.44 that I'd prioritize understanding first. The value it unlocks is proportional to how much WebSocket-dependent code you have, but if you have any meaningful amount, the ROI on learning this API is high.

---

## Upgrade Considerations

Playwright 1.44 requires Node.js 18 or later. If you're still running 16.x in CI, that's the only forced upgrade before you can adopt these features. The migration from 16 to 18 is straightforward for most test setups, but it's worth running your full suite once against Node 18 before committing the Playwright upgrade to main.

Browser binaries will need to be refreshed with `npx playwright install`, which you probably already have in your CI provisioning step. Nothing unusual there.

On the code side, there are no breaking changes in 1.44 that affected any of the three codebases I upgraded. The release notes flag a few deprecated APIs with warnings rather than errors, so you'll see some noise in output if you're using older locator patterns, but nothing will break on the first upgrade.

My recommendation: adopt aria snapshots and `--only-failures` immediately—both are low-risk and high-value. The WebSocket routing deserves a dedicated spike if you have real-time features in scope. The clock improvements are a quiet upgrade that you'll benefit from passively once you're on 1.44.

Upgrade incrementally, run your smoke suite first, and give the new APIs a week of real usage before you commit to structural refactoring around them. That's the approach that's served me well across every Playwright release, and 1.44 is no exception.
